You are fixing a real bug found during Phase 5c analysis of the "kinodynamic certified action shield" track for GO-DynURPlanner. Read `code/KINODYNAMIC_ROADMAP.md`'s Phase 5 section (the Phase 5c checklist entry) and `code/experiments/results/m6_kinodynamic/ANALYSIS.md` IN FULL first — that document has the complete root-cause analysis; do not re-derive it, just implement the fix it recommends. Then read `code/godynur/env.py`'s `_step_velocity` method in full, and `code/experiments/m6_kinodynamic_shield.py`'s training loop (around lines 213-249) in full.

## The bug, briefly

`DynArmEnv._step_velocity` can silently execute a DIFFERENT jerk sequence than what the RL actor's nominal action `u_t` requested (via the accept/fallback/emergency branching — this is correct, intentional safety behavior, not a bug in itself). The bug is downstream: `m6_kinodynamic_shield.py`'s training loop stores the actor's RAW nominal action `a` in the TD3 replay buffer (`agent.buffer.add(s, a, r, s2, ...)`), even on the ~20% of steps where the shield substituted something else. This makes `(s, a, r, s2)` an inconsistent transition — `s2` reflects what the shield actually did, not what `a` would have done — which corrupts a fifth of all stored training data and is the leading hypothesis for why the `kinodynamic_shield` arm failed to learn at all in the Phase 5b run (never advanced past curriculum stage 0 in any of 5 seeds).

## Fix, part 1: `code/godynur/env.py`

In `_step_velocity`, after the accept/fallback/emergency branching determines `q_new, v_new, a_new` (whichever path ran) and BEFORE the final re-clip/state-update lines, compute the "effective executed action" — the `u` value that, fed through the SAME nominal mapping `v_nom = v_old + dv_scale * u_t` the actor uses, would have produced the ACTUAL velocity change that was executed:

```
u_executed = (v_new - v_old) / dv_scale   # elementwise, v_old is self.v BEFORE this step's update
```

Store this as a new instance attribute, e.g. `self._last_executed_action = np.clip(u_executed, -1.0, 1.0)` (clip defensively — the actor's action space is `[-1,1]`; the shield's conservative braking jerks should normally stay within that range but clip anyway so this never hands the training loop an out-of-distribution label). Set this on EVERY call to `_step_velocity` (accept, fallback, AND emergency paths all need it — don't only set it in one branch). Make sure `v_old` is captured before any mutation (check the existing code — `v_old = self.v.copy()` may already exist near the top of the method from Phase 3/4; reuse it, don't introduce a second copy with different timing).

This is purely additive observability — do not change any existing safety/certification logic, constraint, or control flow in `_step_velocity`. The existing 78 tests must all still pass unmodified.

Add a test in `code/tests/test_env_velocity_mode.py` (append): after a normal accepted step with a known `u_t` and no intervention, assert `env._last_executed_action` is close to the original `u_t` (since nothing was substituted, the "effective executed action" should recover the original request). After a step that triggers the fallback path (reuse the existing near-limit test scenario from that file), assert `env._last_executed_action` is DIFFERENT from the original requested action (proving the relabeling actually does something different when the shield intervenes — this is the property that matters, don't just check it "exists").

## Fix, part 2: `code/experiments/m6_kinodynamic_shield.py`

In the training loop (around line 239-240), for the `kinodynamic_shield` arm specifically, store `env._last_executed_action` in the replay buffer instead of the raw `a`:

```python
s2, r, done = env.step(a)
buffer_action = env._last_executed_action if arm == "kinodynamic_shield" else a
agent.buffer.add(s, buffer_action, r, s2, float(done))
```

Do NOT change this for `no_shield` or `ape2_shield` — they don't have this problem (their `a` already reflects what was executed, `ape2_shield`'s shield runs before `env.step()` sees the action). Also check the WARMUP_STEPS random-exploration branch (`a = env.sample_action()`, around line 219) — during warmup for `kinodynamic_shield`, `a` is random and still gets fed through `env.step(a)`, so the SAME relabeling applies there too; make sure the buffer-storage line covers both the warmup and post-warmup branches (it should, if you put the relabeling logic right before the shared `agent.buffer.add` call rather than duplicating it in both branches).

## Validate the fix actually works — run a short training probe, don't just trust the code change

Run a short `kinodynamic_shield`-only training run to sanity-check the fix has a real effect (this is the actual acceptance criterion, not just "the code compiles"):

```bash
cd code && source .venv/bin/activate && OMP_NUM_THREADS=4 MKL_NUM_THREADS=4 OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS=4 NUMEXPR_NUM_THREADS=4 PYTHONPATH=. python experiments/m6_kinodynamic_shield.py --episodes 400 --seeds 1 --seed-salt 100 --arms kinodynamic_shield --out /tmp/m6_fix_probe
```

(Use `--seed-salt 100` so this probe's seed doesn't collide with the already-committed `--seed-salt 0` results; write output to `/tmp/m6_fix_probe`, NOT into the tracked `experiments/results/m6_kinodynamic/` directory — this is a validation probe, not a result to commit.) Compare against the ALREADY-COMMITTED `--seed-salt 0` seed 0 result at the same 400-episode checkpoint (`experiments/results/m6_kinodynamic/m6_uoar_kinodynamic_shield_salt0.json`, seed "0", the `episode: 400` entry — succ was 0.03 there). Report whether the fixed run shows ANY sign of improvement (higher success, curriculum advancing past stage 0, or a declining intervention rate) — if it looks just as stuck, say so plainly rather than declaring victory; the buffer-consistency bug might be A cause but not the ONLY cause, and an honest "still stuck, here's what I observed" is a fine outcome to report. Do not spend more than this one short probe run's worth of time on further debugging — if the fix doesn't obviously help, report the finding and stop; further investigation is a separate follow-up dispatch, not this one.

## Constraints

- Do NOT modify `continuous.py`, `ape2.py`, `td3.py`, `grid_td3.py`, `forecast.py`, `voxelizer.py`, `scenes.py`, `policy.py`, `panda.py`, `kinodynamics.py`, `safety_qp.py`. Only `env.py` (additive attribute only), `m6_kinodynamic_shield.py` (the buffer-storage line + the WARMUP_STEPS branch check), and `test_env_velocity_mode.py`.
